GO Enrichment Analysis of CESA Knockout DEGs

Kerrina Whelan

2025-04-30

Introduction

This report summarizes Gene Ontology (GO) enrichment analysis results for biological processes (BP), molecular functions (MF), and cellular components (CC) using PANTHER data. The analysis includes barplots and pie charts to visualize significant GO terms. The GO enrichment was performed on differentially expressed genes (DEGs) identified from RNA-seq data in a CESA knockout mutant of Physcomitrium patens.

GO Bar Plot (Top 15 Biological Processes)

A bar plot of the top 15 enriched biological processes was created based on fold enrichment values. This exploratory figure provided an initial functional classification of CESA knockout DEGs to guide deeper statistical analysis of biological processes.

Figure 1. Secondary metabolism, transport, and cell wall biogenesis processes are enriched in CESA knockout DEGs. GO enrichment analysis was performed on DEGs from P. patens CESA knockout lines (n = 3 biological replicates) using the PANTHER classification system. Fold enrichment and FDR-adjusted p-values were calculated for biological process (BP) terms. Only terms with FDR < 0.05 were retained, and the top 15 enriched BP terms were plotted. Bars represent fold enrichment for each GO term, with color intensity indicating enrichment magnitude. Enriched biological processes include secondary metabolism, cytoskeleton-dependent cytokinesis, water transport, and cell wall biogenesis, suggesting that CESA disruption activates metabolic, transport, and structural remodeling pathways.

GO Pie Charts (BP, MF, CC)

Pie charts were generated to summarize the distribution of GO terms across biological process, molecular function, and cellular component categories. These figures provided an overview of the types of activities and cellular locations affected by CESA knockout.

Figure 2. CESA knockout DEGs are associated with intracellular organelles, glycosyltransferase activity, and secondary metabolic processes. GO enrichment analysis was performed on DEGs from P. patens CESA knockout lines (n = 3 biological replicates) using the PANTHER classification system. Significant GO terms (FDR < 0.05) were grouped into cellular component (CC), molecular function (MF), and biological process (BP) categories. B) Cellular Component: DEGs were predominantly associated with intracellular organelles and membrane compartments.C) Molecular Function: Glycosyltransferase and water transport-related activities were highly represented. D) Biological Process: Secondary metabolic processes and cell wall organization were key enriched processes, suggesting metabolic and structural reprogramming in response to CESA loss.

GO Combined Bar Plot and Pie Charts

For clarity and conciseness, the GO bar plot and pie charts were merged into a single figure summarizing DEG functions. This gives a cohesive view of the types of biological activities, molecular roles, and cellular structures affected by CESA disruption and provides context for interpreting statistical enrichment results presented in the GO and KEGG analysis.

Figure 3. CESA knockout DEGs are enriched in secondary metabolism, transport, and cell wall biogenesis processes and localize to intracellular organelles. GO enrichment analysis was performed on DEGs from P. patens CESA knockout lines (n = 3 biological replicates) using the PANTHER classification system. A) The bar plot displays the top 15 enriched biological processes (BP) based on fold enrichment, filtered for FDR < 0.05. BD) Pie charts summarize the distribution of enriched cellular components (CC), molecular functions (MF), and biological processes (BP). A) Biological processes were enriched for secondary metabolism, cytoskeleton-dependent cytokinesis, water transport, and cell wall biogenesis. B) Cellular components were predominantly intracellular organelles and membrane-bound structures. C) Molecular functions included glycosyltransferase activity and water transport-related activities. D) Biological process distribution confirmed the dominance of secondary metabolic and cell wall-related processes, highlighting the metabolic and structural reprogramming triggered by CESA loss.
